{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655855"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:06:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:06:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18687"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18687"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76845"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11419"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18687"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62350"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10298"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26457"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76845"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIonotropic receptors are important components of fast synaptic transmission in the nervous system. They are activated when neurotransmitters bind to specific sites on the receptor.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of ionotropic receptors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Production of cyclic adenosine monophosphate","Stimulation of G-protein cascades","Direct ion channel opening upon ligand binding","Activation of second messenger systems","Phosphorylation of membrane proteins"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism involves \u003Cstrong\u003Edirect ion channel opening upon ligand binding\u003C/strong\u003E. When a neurotransmitter binds to an ionotropic receptor, it causes an immediate conformational change that opens an ion channel within the receptor complex. This allows specific ions to flow across the membrane, producing rapid changes in membrane potential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of second messenger systems\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of metabotropic receptors, not ionotropic receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhosphorylation of membrane proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a downstream effect of second messenger cascades, not a direct mechanism of ionotropic receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of cyclic adenosine monophosphate\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a second messenger pathway used by metabotropic receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulation of G-protein cascades\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes G-protein coupled receptors, which are metabotropic\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe direct coupling between ligand binding and channel opening allows ionotropic receptors to mediate very rapid synaptic responses, typically within milliseconds.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ionotropic receptors contain an ion channel that opens directly when a ligand binds.","Ligand binding causes a conformational change that allows specific ions to flow through the channel.","Ionotropic receptors produce rapid responses compared to metabotropic receptors which work through second messenger systems."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62350"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18687"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62350"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T14:04:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T14:05:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11419"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76845"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group"